                           ##############
                           #   README   #
                           ##############

--------> Available tests <----------

1) Energy deposit of electron beams in slabs and multilayer
2) Electromagnetic physics is active only.

--------> Set-up <----------
setup with:
compiler = gcc-3.2
G4SYSTEM = linux-g++

The following environment variables need to be set:
G4LEDATA: points to low energy data base - G4EMLOW4.0
Analisys = AIDA 3.2.1 and PI 1.3.3

--------> How to run <----------
1) batch mode
$G4WORKDIR/bin/Linux-g++/test52 file.in

2) interactive mode
$G4WORKDIR/bin/Linux-g++/test52

---------------------------------------------------------------------*
default macro file is initialised ---> default.mac                   *
in interactive mode         
                                                                     *
experimental set-up fixed by default.mac                             
---------------------------------------------------------------------

--------> Primary particles  <----------

a monochromatic electron beam is generated with:
default energy = 1. MeV
position = (0., 0., -1. m)
direction = (0., 0., 1)

The user can change interactively these parameters with the following
interactive commands:

* /gun/energy 0.5 MeV
* /gun/position 
* /gun/direction

--------> Modular Physics <----------

choice of physics lists:

--> gamma    - photon-standard (Standard Processes)
             - photon-epdl     (LowEnergy Processes)
             - photon-penelope (Penelope Processes)

--> e-       - electron-standard (Standard Processes)
             - electron-eedl     (LowEnergyProcesses)
	     - electron-penelope (Penelope Processes)
             
--> e+       - positron-standard (Standard Processes)         
             - positron-penelope (Penelope Processes)

example of macros:
- lowe.mac
- standard.mac
- penelope.mac

Default cut = 0.001*mm
Default facrange = 0.02

--------> Experimental set-up <----------

The target is contained in a World volume (box with size 40. m); 
the world volume is made of vacuum.

 Target default z size is: 10. mm
 Target default x half size is: 20 m                                      
 Target default y half size is: 20 m            

The target is made by aluminum by default.

The user can change the Z size of the box with the interactive command:
/target/setTargetThick 5. mm


The user can change the material of the box with the interactive command:
/target/setTargetMat Iron
#/target/update

* Available materials:
Hydrogen Beryllium Graphite Nytrogen Oxygen Magnesium Aluminium Silicon
liquidArgon Titanium Iron Cobalt Nickel Copper Zinc Gallium
Germanium Zirconium Molybdenium Silver Cadmium Indium Tin
Cesium Samarium Ytterbium Tantalum Gold Lead Uranium Water Quartz Air

The Ionisation Mean Excitation Energy of all the materials has been changed to 
the NIST referece data.

--------> Energy deposit <----------

The energy deposit is calculated in slices perpendicular to the electron beam 
direction:
           ----
----->    |    |
e- beam   |    |
           ----

--------------------->
                   z

The energy deposit derives from the interactions of primary and 
secondary particles in the target.

The number of voxels along the Z axis in 100 by default.
This parameter can be changed interactively with the command:
/target/voxelNumber 200

The RO Geometry, the sensitive detector, the analysis are updated automatically

--------> Simulation Parameters <----------

1) Max step:
The max step in the target is fixed for all the particles 
involved in the experimental set-up (e-, e+, gamma).
The maximum step is fixed to 1 * micrometer.

The user can change this parameter with the interactive command
/target/setMaxStep 0.1 * cm

2) Cut:
The threshold of production of secondary particles is fixed to 0.1 * mm by default.
The default value can be changed through the interactive command:
/physics/cutE 10. * mm

3) FacRange
The default value of the facrange is 0.02.
The user can change this value for positrons and electrons
with the interactive command:
/physics/facRange 0.005


--------> Output <----------
test52.hbk

Histogram 10: energy deposit with respect to depth.
The energy deposit is stored whenever there is a hit in the target.
The error depends on the square root of the hits.

Histogram 20: Energy deposit per event

Histogram 30: Energy of secondary electron (MeV) generated by ionization

Histogram 40: Energy of secondary photons (MeV)

Histogram 50: Energy of secondary electron (MeV) generated by 
	      photoelectric effect